          <p class='first-para'>
            I agree that that problem needs to be resolved. The hon. Gentleman will know that one of the inspection's conclusions is that it is more difficult to reach agreement in two-tier areas than in unitary areas, but that agreement can be reached provided that there is a management culture in the agencies and a commitment by senior executives. I agree that it is important in two-tier areas that counties and districts work closely together in pursuit of the common objective.</p><p>
            My key point is the message that clearly comes out of the inspection report: it is difficult for the partner agencies to decide how to prioritise the various plans with which they are required to comply and which take up much of senior executives' time and energy. A manager in a health authority told the inspection that
            <q>the planning cycles for health-related plans did not coincide with community safety planning cycles.</q>
            The inspectors summarised the problem by stating:
            <q>A consistent message was that government departments, such as the Home Office, DETR, DfEE and the Department of Health, could work better together and thereby assist local partnerships by co-ordinating their own work and their liaison with local agencies.</q>
            The agenda for action states:
            <q>Inspectors urged Ministers to improve strategic co-ordination of planning processes to ensure that all plans, national and local, support each other and do not require energy to be invested in planning to the detriment of service delivery.</q>
            A comparable criticism is made of the funding and bidding process. As the Minister said in his introductory remarks, much of the moneys that the Home Office put into crime reduction strategies is available in the form of
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_274wh' title='Col. 274WH &mdash; HC Deb 27 July 2000 vol 354 c274WH' name='column_274wh' href='#column_274wh' rel='bookmark'>274WH</a>
            challenge funding for which partnerships or their constituent agencies must present bids. The irony is that the Government complained to the inspectors that many of the bids were of poor quality, and local authorities and police forces told the inspectors that they were concerned about the complexity and inconsistency of the bidding process, which wasted so much time and effort.</p><p>
            On page 19 of the report, a director of housing in one local authority is quoted as saying:
            <q>The notification period and time to react and respond is woefully short&#x2026; This is valuable time, which could have been utilised far more productively on existing well proven initiatives.</q>
            It is important to get challenge funding right. Both political parties have viewed it as a valuable means of encouraging innovation and experiment and of ensuring that moneys follow genuine fresh thinking, rather than being doled out to support continuing projects year after year without review. We must, however, guard against the risk that flashy new challenge funding initiatives become a substitute for effective work already taking place on the ground that did not previously require extra form filling, extra chasing after funds and so forth.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
